                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d782">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">352.115/148: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Third Secretary of Embassy in Spain</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wendelin</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-10-30T20:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 30, 1936—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>180. In a telegram received by Department October 28,<note n="78"
                        xml:id="d782fn78">Not printed.</note> the Consul General at Barcelona
                    reports that the International Banking Corporation has received a communication
                    from the Industrial Cotton <pb facs="0850" n="751" xml:id="pg_751"/> Committee
                    in Barcelona stating that it had assumed possession, for the purpose of
                    distribution, of cotton taken over in Barcelona.</p>
                <p>Please bring the matter to the attention of the Foreign Office and say that in
                    the event that the American shippers do not receive payment from the authorities
                    in Barcelona this Government will be under the necessity of looking to the
                    Government of Spain for payment in full of all cotton taken over.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Carr</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
